article.description: Freshman Sylvia Fowles had 17 points and 16 rebounds and Seimone Augustus scored 16 points, leading No. 2 LSU to a 65-51 victory over Temple on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Fowles' double-double leads Tigers past Temple
article.linkText: Fowles over Owls: Freshman leads No. 2 LSU
article.story:
PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Sylvia Fowles made quite an impression on
three-time Olympian Dawn Staley.

The freshman center had 17 points and 16 rebounds and Seimone
Augustus scored 16 points, leading No. 2 LSU to a 65-51 victory
over Temple on Tuesday night.

"She's a ringer," Temple coach Staley said of Fowles. "We
watched her from afar, hoping to get a player like her. She's got a
lot of promise and upside. I fear for LSU's opponents, especially
when she gets more experience."

The 6-foot-5 Fowles, a reserve for the Lady Tigers, is averaging
11.4 points, 8.8 rebounds and 3 blocks.

"I just went out there and did what I had to do," Fowles said.

Scholanda Hoston and Wendlyn Jones each added nine points for
the Lady Tigers (5-0).

Cynthia Jordan and Candice Dupree had 14 points apiece for
Temple (1-1).

LSU coach Pokey Chatman said Fowles will only get better.

"She's not satisfied with that performance. She probably
doesn't even know how many points or rebounds she had," Chatman
said.

The Owls, who trailed by 11 early in the second half, got within
48-45 on a 3-pointer by Ashley Morris with 7:33 left.

But Tillie Willis scored a basket, Fowles made a layup and
Hoston added a running layup, giving LSU a 54-45 lead. The Owls
never got closer than nine, with LSU hitting seven consecutive
shots in a span of 6:34 down the stretch.

"It boiled down to us establishing ourselves on the glass and
getting second-chance points," Chatman said.

LSU outrebounded Temple 48-33.

The Lady Tigers have won four of five games by double-digit
margins. The other victory was 71-70 over then-No. 8 Baylor on Nov.
14.

LSU was sluggish at the start, missing eight of its first nine
shots. The Lady Tigers didn't get their second basket until Jones
made a layup 5:01 into the game.

Temple kept it close over the next 10 minutes, but LSU pulled
away with a 12-4 in the last 6:15 of the half to take a 32-19 lead
at the break. Augustus scored eight of her points during that run,
beginning with a layup and hitting three straight jumpers.

"We've won two Atlantic 10 championships because of playing
schedules like this," Staley said. "One of these days we're going
to beat one of these giants. We're getting close. We can taste
it."

Philadelphia Eagles quarterback Donovan McNabb and several
teammates were among the crowd of 1,127 at the Liacouras Center.
